That crash is not an ML failure. It is a Hugging Face network/cache failure that happened at a terrible time.

Your run had made excellent progress:

✓ NAICS trained
✓ qe4ar trained
✓ qe5ar semantic memory completed
✗ crashed while starting qe5ar feature embeddings

The key failure is this:

[WinError 10060] ... while requesting HEAD https://huggingface.co/BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5/resolve/main/adapter_config.json
...
RuntimeError: Cannot send a request, as the client has been closed.

That means sentence-transformers / transformers tried to contact Hugging Face to check optional model files while loading BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5 again. The model itself is already cached, but the library still tried HTTP HEAD checks for files like:

adapter_config.json
processor_config.json
preprocessor_config.json
video_preprocessor_config.json

Your network timed out, retries happened, and then the Hugging Face HTTP client tripped over itself. Hugging Face documents HF_HUB_OFFLINE=1 as the switch that prevents HTTP calls and forces use of cached files only. Transformers also documents HF_HUB_OFFLINE=1 and local_files_only=True for cache-only loading.  ￼

What to do now

Do not panic-delete caches. The expensive embedding caches survived:

C:\laborshed_autocode\embedding_cache\NAICS_semantic_memory_93d8de836486b01b1cb632ce.npy
C:\laborshed_autocode\embedding_cache\NAICS_semantic_memory_cc9994ade25e7f3eefb177b6.npy
C:\laborshed_autocode\embedding_cache\qe4ar_SOC_semantic_memory_b8871340854a1eab31f7d847.npy
C:\laborshed_autocode\embedding_cache\feature_embeddings_fit_b8871340854a1eab31f7d847.npy
C:\laborshed_autocode\embedding_cache\qe5ar_SOC_semantic_memory_181fb3dd24a29827fe630aea.npy

The next restart should use those caches and should be run in offline Hugging Face mode so the script does not try to call the internet mid-run.

Step 1: Confirm the failed process is gone

Run:

Get-CimInstance Win32_Process |
  Where-Object {
    $_.Name -like "python*" -and
    $_.CommandLine -like "*naics_soc*autocoder.py*"
  } |
  Select-Object ProcessId, CreationDate, CommandLine |
  Format-List

If no autocoder process appears, good.

If one is still running, stop it:

Stop-Process -Id 34804

Replace 34804 with the actual process ID.

Step 2: Check whether a model file was saved

Because the crash happened during train_full_bundle(), the final model probably was not saved. Check:

Test-Path "C:\laborshed_autocode\naics_soc_gpu_lane1.joblib"
Test-Path "C:\laborshed_autocode\naics_soc_gpu_lane1.joblib.summary.json"
Test-Path "C:\laborshed_autocode\laborshed_scored_gpu_lane1.sav"

If these return False, you need to restart train_and_score.

If a .joblib exists, check its timestamp:

Get-Item "C:\laborshed_autocode\naics_soc_gpu_lane1.joblib" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
  Select-Object LastWriteTime, Length, FullName

If it was not written after the crash point, do not rely on it.

Step 3: Verify the Hugging Face model can load offline

This is the most important test before restarting the big run.

Run exactly this:

cd C:\laborshed_autocode
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
$env:HF_HUB_OFFLINE="1"
$env:TRANSFORMERS_OFFLINE="1"
$env:HF_HUB_DISABLE_PROGRESS_BARS="1"
$env:TOKENIZERS_PARALLELISM="false"
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe -c "from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer; import torch; print('cuda', torch.cuda.is_available()); m=SentenceTransformer('BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5', device='cuda'); print('loaded offline ok')"

Expected output:

cuda True
loaded offline ok

If that works, restart the autocoder offline.

If it fails with “could not find files in cache,” then the model is not cached in the cache location being used by that terminal. In that case, temporarily turn offline off and cache it once:

Remove-Item Env:\HF_HUB_OFFLINE -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
Remove-Item Env:\TRANSFORMERS_OFFLINE -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe -c "from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer; SentenceTransformer('BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5', device='cuda'); print('cached')"

Then repeat the offline test.

Step 4: Optional but recommended, log in to Hugging Face

This is not enough by itself, because your problem was network instability, but it prevents rate-limit/auth warnings.

cd C:\laborshed_autocode
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
python -m pip install -U huggingface_hub
hf auth login
hf auth whoami

Use a read-only token.

Do not set:

$env:HF_TOKEN = ""

Hugging Face documents that HF_TOKEN, when set, overrides the token stored on your machine. An empty/bad token can create weird behavior.  ￼

